<DOC><DOCNO> AP880304-0078 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-03-04-88 0638EST</FILEID><FIRST>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     03-04 0643</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0666</SECOND><HEAD>Ice Storm In Ohio Valley, Showers In South</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   A storm coated parts of the Midwest with ice and snow, whilerain fell in much of the South and sections of the West Coast. Snowalso fell in the nation's central region.   Freezing rain was reported across central Indiana into centralOhio late Thursday. Overpasses and bridges in Indiana were coveredby up to 2 inches of ice, resulting in numerous accidents and poweroutages.   A half-inch of ice was reported in Ohio, where slippery roadswere blamed for at least four highway fatalities.   Three to 8 inches of new snow was reported across parts ofnorthern Indiana and northern Ohio, including 6 inches at Peru,Ind., and Findlay, Ohio.   Snow also fell from Pennsylvania and much of New York intocentral parts of New England. One to 3 inches was reported lateThursday across parts of northern Pennsylvania, with up to 6 inchesexpected.   Up to 3 inches of snow was reported at Binghamton, N.Y., lateThursday, and up to 6 inches was expected in central New York bythe time the storm ended today.   Showers and thunderstorms dampened the Mississippi and Tennesseevalleys through the Gulf Coast into northern Florida. Heavy rain,small hail and gusty winds accompanied the storms across the South.   More than 3{ inches of rain was reported in the 24 hours endingat about 2 a.m. at Tallahassee, Fla., and nearly 3 inches at NewOrleans.   Snow developed late Thursday across southeast Kansas, southwestMissouri, northeast Oklahoma and northwest Arkansas. Nearly an inchfell early today at Monett, Mo., and 1 to 3 inches was reportedacross southeast Kansas late Thursday.   Light rain was scattered across eastern Montana along astationary front that reached from southern Alberta into thenorthern High Plains. Snow was falling across parts ofnorth-central Wyoming.   A frontal system off the Pacific Coast brought scatteredrainshowers along the coast of Oregon and northwest California.   For today, snow was forecast from northern and westernPennsylvania across New York and New England; scattered rain orsnow across southeast Missouri, southern Illinois, and northernsections of the Ohio Valley; rain from Kentucky and Tennesseethrough the middle Atlantic Coast region, with showers andthunderstorms likely over northern Florida, Alabama, Georgia andthe Carolinas; scattered rain or snow showers across the northernhigh Plains; snowshowers widely scattered over the mountains ofWyoming and Colorado; and rain across the Pacific Northwest.   Much of the nation will have highs in the 40s or 50s. Highs willbe in the 20s and 30s from the Dakotas through the Great Lakes andNew England; in the 30s in the middle Mississippi Valley andnorthern sections of the Ohio Valley; the 60s and 70s fromCalifornia across the desert Southwest, and from southern andcentral Texas to the southern half of the Atlantic Coast; and about80 over southern and central Florida.   Temperatures around the nation at 2 a.m. EST ranged from 6 belowzero at Marquette, Mich., to 74 at Miami.   Other reports:   _East: Atlanta 58 rain; Boston 34 drizzle; Buffalo 27 cloudy;Charleston, S.C. 60 showery; Cincinnati 31 foggy; Cleveland 25snow; Detroit 21 partly cloudy; Miami 73 partly cloudy; New York 42foggy; Philadelphia 43 foggy; Pittsburgh 32 rain; Portland, Maine29 snow; Washington 44 foggy.   _Central: Bismarck, N.D. 24 fair; Chicago 26 partly cloudy;Dallas-Fort Worth 36 fair; Denver 33 fair; Des Moines 20 fair;Indianapolis 28 cloudy; Kansas City 25 fair; Minneapolis-St. Paul19 fair; Nashville 60 showery; New Orleans 65 foggy; St. Louis 28cloudy.   _West: Albuquerque 35 fair; Anchorage 34 cloudy; Las Vegas 55cloudy; Los Angeles 58 cloudy; Phoenix 57 fair; Salt Lake City 47partly cloudy; San Diego 57 cloudy; San Francisco 51 partly cloudy;Seattle 40 cloudy.   _Canada: Montreal 10 fair; Toronto 16 partly cloudy.</TEXT></DOC>